==English==

===Etymology===
[[frequentative|Frequentative]] of ''[[daze]]''.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ËˆdÃ¦zÉ™l/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|Ã¦zÉ™l|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|dazzl}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To confuse the [[sight]] of by means of excessive brightness.
#: '''''Dazzled''' by the headlights of the lorry, the deer stopped in the middle of the street.''
#* Milton
#*: Those heavenly shapes / Will '''dazzle''' now the earthly, with their blaze / Insufferably bright.
#* Sir H. Taylor
#*: An unreflected light did never yet / '''Dazzle''' the vision feminine.
# {{lb|en|transitive|figuratively}} To [[render]] [[incapable]] of thinking clearly; to overwhelm with showiness or brilliance.
#: ''The delegates were '''dazzled''' by the originality of his arguments.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To be overpowered by light; to be confused by excess of brightness.
#* Francis Bacon
#*: An overlight maketh the eyes '''dazzle'''.
#* Dryden
#*: I dare not trust these eyes; / They dance in mists, and '''dazzle''' with surprise.

